, and they\'ll win the game!\r\n\r\nThere are so many things you can do with this game to turn it into a polished, multi-page game that your friends and family can play. Try adding new pages, buttons to go to the next or previous page, and if you\'re really ambitious, try adding a high-score tracker! Play around with the code, get it working the way you want it to, and have fun!","Where\'s Waldo? - Part Four","","inherit","closed","closed","","79-revision-v1","","","2017-10-27 14:22:31","2017-10-27 14:22:31","",79,"http://evingrost.dev/79-revision-v1/",0,"revision","",0),
(92,1,"2017-10-27 14:57:36","2017-10-27 14:57:36","In this final section of our Where\'s Waldo tutorial, we will put everything together to create a working game that you can play with your friends and family! We\'ll use our server to verify if the correct coordinates were clicked, then give feedback to the user once they\'ve found Waldo and won the game. Let\'s get started.\r\n\r\n<h2>A Coordinated Effort</h2>\r\n\r\nAs of now, we have no way of verifying whether the x- and y-coordinates that are sent to the server are correct. In order to solve this issue, we\'ll need to write a simple function in Ruby. We\'ll want to create a new ruby file within our general \"Waldo\" folder, and name it what you\'d like. Here, I call mine \"rubyFunctions.rb\".\r\n\r\nAfter we\'ve made our file, we need to find out the range of x- and y-coordinates that are acceptable for the user to click on to be considered a \"hit\" for Waldo. This can be done in many ways. There are websites that will show you the x- and y-coordinates of where you click on an uploaded image, or you can simply <span class=\"inline__code\">console.log(e.offsetX + \",\" + e.offsetY);</span> and click on the corners of Waldo to find the range of acceptable coordinates. In the case of this image, the range of acceptable x-coordinates are 380 - 419, and y-coordinates are 262-302.\r\n\r\nNow that we know the acceptable coordinate range, we can build our validation function in ruby. In your \"rubyFunctions.rb\" file, enter the following code:\r\n\r\n<pre><span class=\"code__block\">def validateXY(x, y)\r\n   intX = x.to_i\r\n   intY = y.to_i\r\n   if (intX &gt; 380) &amp;&amp; (intX &lt; 419) &amp;&amp; (intY &gt; 262) &amp;&amp; (intY &lt; 302)\r\n      return true\r\n   else\r\n      return false\r\n   end\r\nend</span></pre>\r\n\r\nThis simply means that if the coordinates received are within the correct range, return \"true\". If not, return \"false\". Nice and simple!\r\n\r\nHowever, we\'re not done with this step yet. We\'ve set up a validation function, but how do we actually pass our x- and y-coordinates into that function and get the answer back? Let\'s start with the JavaScript.\r\n\r\nEarlier, we talked about how to get the x- and y-coordinates in JavaScript, but we skipped ahead before sending them to the server. In our JS file, we\'ll need to modify our \"getXY\" function in order to call a new \"sendInfoToServer\" function. I\'ve commented the next bit of code line-by-line as it gets a bit complicated:\r\n\r\n<pre><span class=\"code__block\"><span class=\"code__comment\">// This function gets the X and Y coordinates of where the</span>\r\n<span class=\"code__comment\">// user clicked, relative to the image.</span>\r\n   function getXY(e){\r\n      var xPosition = e.offsetX;\r\n      var yPosition = e.offsetY;\r\n      <span class=\"code__comment\">// Sending x and y to the server.</span>\r\n      sendInfoToServer(xPosition, yPosition);\r\n   }\r\n\r\n<span class=\"code__comment\">// Takes the x and y coordinates, passed from the getXY</span>\r\n<span class=\"code__comment\">// function, and sends them to the server to determine whether</span>\r\n<span class=\"code__comment\">// or not these coordinates are correct for Waldo.</span>\r\nfunction sendInfoToServer(x, y){\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// Making a new request.</span>\r\n   var xyRequest = new XMLHttpRequest();\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// This line passes our x and y coordinates into a query</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// string that Sinatra can use and determine what to do with.</span>\r\n   xyRequest.open(\'GET\', \'http://localhost:4567/puzzle01validate?xPos=\' + x + \'&amp;yPos=\' + y);\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// The \"onload\" function executes when the server responds that</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// it received the request. It does what it is instructed to do</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// with those coordinates.</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// Example: If a user clicks \"like\" on a facebook post, when</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// the server responds that it received the request, it will</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// update the number of likes on that post.</span>\r\n   xyRequest.onload = saveScore;\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">//This line sends our request.</span>\r\n   xyRequest.send();\r\n}</span></pre>\r\n\r\nXMLHttpRequest is a function that is built into JS, which allows us to send and recieve information to and from a server. For an in-depth tutorial on how this works, check out <a href=\"https://youtu.be/rJesac0_Ftw\" target=\"_blank\">this video</a>. For now, all we need to know is that we are sending our coordinates to our Sinatra controller through something called a query string. A query string comes through to the server like this: <span class=\"inline__code\">http://localhost:4567/puzzle01validate?xPos=394&amp;yPos=280</span>.\r\n\r\nNow, when our server receives this query string, it will let us know whether the coordinates are \"true\", within the correct range, or \"false\", not within the correct range.\r\n\r\nAs of now, you technically have a working game of Where\'s Waldo! The problem is, there is no visual confirmation that the user got it right when they click on Waldo. The final touch will be in our JavaScript file.\r\n\r\n<pre><span class=\"code__block\">function saveScore(e){\r\n   var response = false;\r\n  \r\n   if (e.target.responseText === \"true\"){\r\n      response = true;\r\n   }\r\n  \r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// This if statement checks to see if \"didYouFindWaldo\"</span>\r\n   <span class=\"code__comment\">// returns true. If so, we move on to stop the timer.</span>\r\n   if (response === true){\r\n      timerData = endTimer();\r\n   }\r\n}</pre></span>\r\n\r\nNow, when the server sends back that the coordinates are true, our JavaScript will fill the modal with the user\'s time, and they\'ll win the game!\r\n\r\nThere are so many things you can do with this game to turn it into a polished, multi-page game that your friends and family can play. Try adding new pages, buttons to go to the next or previous page, and if you\'re really ambitious, try adding a high-score tracker! Play around with the code, get it working the way you want it to, and have fun!","Where\'s Waldo? - Part Four","","inherit","closed","closed","","79-revision-v1","","","2017-10-27 14:57:36","2017-10-27 14:57:36","",79,"http://evingrost.dev/79-revision-v1/",0,"revision","",0),
