(99,1,"2017-11-02 15:36:31","2017-11-02 15:36:31","Whether it\'s finishing up a tedious and long-winded back-end project, finally getting around to fixing that bothersome bug, or even cleaning the house or sticking to a diet, we all have times in our lives when we have trouble getting motivated to do the things that need to get done. Having a vast arsenal of tricks and approaches to get you motivated will help.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Be your own dictator.</h2>\r\nAfter a year and a half of being on the <a href=\"https://www.ruled.me/guide-keto-diet/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Ketogenic diet</a>, I fell off the bandwagon this year when fall came around. The smell of spiced apple cider, the rich orange color of butternut squash soup, pumpkin scented candles and hot apple pie were just too much for me to turn down. After a month of eating all of my favorite fall foods, I knew I needed to get back to taking care of my body, but finding the motivation to get back on track was really tough. One night, I found myself reaching for the caramel apple slices, when my own voice in my head bellowed a loud and firm, \"NO.\" I stopped for a moment and stared at the creamy caramel like a puppy begging for table scraps, but the disciplinarian side of me held steadfast. There was no reasoning, no questioning, no second-guessing. In that moment, I had to tell myself <strong>no</strong>, and there was no way out of it.\r\n\r\nIn these moments, I conjure up images of my mother telling me no. I would always ask her, \"but why,\" and the answer was always the same: <em>because I said so</em>. Sometimes this is exactly the approach you need to take toward completing a particular goal. Can I just play my game for 5 more minutes? No. Can I just finish up this front-end animation that I\'m having fun with first? No. Can I just finish replying to this tweet before I finish my paper? <strong>No.</strong>\r\n\r\nThis approach is one of the most effective for me in the short-term, but it isn\'t for everyone. Being your own dictator takes a lot of self-discipline, especially in the moment, but there are many other ways to tackle getting motivated.\r\n<h2>Set up a rewards system.</h2>\r\nIf you\'ve ever owned a pet, you\'ll know that animals will do just about anything for a treat. My cat knows \"sit\", \"lay down\", and \"out\" better than a lot of people\'s dogs. She\'ll do anything for a tuna snack. <strong>Anything.</strong>\r\n\r\nReward systems are one of the most basic psychological motivators among living things. If I told you that I\'ll give you one million dollars if you clean your room right now, I imagine you\'d probably do it. While that\'s a cartoonish example, it goes to show that we are motivated for treats or rewards the same as our dogs and cats. With that in mind, you can set yourself up for success by creating your own reward system.\r\n\r\nMost people who use this approach will set food as the reward (my all-time favorite are those marshmallow Pinwheel cookies that are probably 1000 calories each), but I would encourage you to get creative. Maybe there\'s a band coming to town that you\'ve always wanted to see. Maybe you love going out to happy hour with your friends on Friday evenings after work. My ultimate reward is getting to go out to karaoke night with all of my best friends. No matter what the reward, the concept is simple: if I accomplish my goal, I get the reward.\r\n\r\nOf course, you need to hold fast to the rules on this one. If you didn\'t accomplish the goal, you cannot have the reward.\r\n<h2>Be a slave to the schedule.</h2>\r\nOften times when I\'m feeling under-motivated to finish a tedious task, I\'m looking for someone to blame; somewhere to direct my frustration. Keeping a schedule can fulfill that need while helping you to not waste time in the process. Allowing yourself to be a slave to your schedule can help get things done on time and with no excuses. Your best friend calls to ask you out to tea? Sorry, I can\'t. The schedule says I need to be cleaning the house.\r\n\r\nHaving a hand-written schedule makes a big difference for me. If I grab a pen and actually write down my schedule in a book, it helps me to remember it\'s there, and gives it an unconscious sense of authority. That doesn\'t mean that we can\'t also have a digital schedule as well. Google Calendar keeps me on track for more long-term projects, <a href=\"https://trello.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Trello</a> helps me with my web development projects, and the alarm on my phone rules my everyday life.\r\n\r\nIf you think it\'s possible that you\'re going to slip up, you can also set witty alarms to nag you into doing what you need to do. If I\'m supposed to be cleaning the kitchen at 11:00, I\'ll set an alarm at 11:05 that says \"You better be cleaning the kitchen.\" At 11:10, \"Seriously, stop messing around and get to cleaning.\" 11:15 - \"I\'m not going to stop nagging you until you get this done.\" 11:18 - \"It\'s only going to get worse from here.\" Once I\'ve started my task, I get to disable all other alarms, and my phone leaves me alone. I have no choice, I\'m a slave to the schedule.\r\n<h2>Set yourself to auto-pilot.</h2>\r\nWe don\'t give enough credit to the amazing phenomenon of muscle memory. For most of us, when we wake up early in the morning to get ready for school or work, we\'re essentially on auto-pilot. We aren\'t really thinking; our muscles just know what to do and how to get ready\r\n<h2>Enlist help.</h2>\r\n<h2>Let music set the pace.</h2>\r\n<h2>Don\'t give in to guilt.</h2>\r\nHow many times has this happened to you or someone you know: You go to a grocery store and stuff your cart full of every organic vegetable, grass-fed meat, and nutritious \"superfood\" you can find. You\'ve decided to start on a new healthy eating plan and you\'re jumping in head-first. You\'re off to a good start, but three days later, it\'s your best friend\'s birthday party. You give in to temptation and take a cookie or a slice of cake. Everything is ruined. You couldn\'t even make it four days, what were you thinking? Well, you might as well just eat 10 cookies, half a cake, and 3 ropes of licorice, because you\'ve ruined the diet anyway, what does it matter now?\r\n\r\nThat\'s guilt talking. We\'re all human; we have needs, desires, and momentary lapses in judgement where we make mistakes. The first thing to keep in mind is that feeling guilty about a mistake can lead to very destructive behavior. You ate a cookie. So what? It was good, enjoy it. Now, you\'ve had your fun, and it\'s time to recommit to that healthy eating lifestyle. Maybe you set a goal to fix that bug last night, but instead you binge watched Stranger Things 2 until 1 AM. It\'s okay. Forgive yourself, then recommit and set a new goal in the morning.","","","inherit","closed","closed","","97-revision-v1","","","2017-11-02 15:36:31","2017-11-02 15:36:31","",97,"http://evingrost.dev/97-revision-v1/",0,"revision","",0),
(100,1,"2017-11-02 15:54:08","2017-11-02 15:54:08","Whether it\'s finishing up a tedious and long-winded back-end project, finally getting around to fixing that bothersome bug, or even cleaning the house or sticking to a diet, we all have times in our lives when we have trouble getting motivated to do the things that need to get done. Having a vast arsenal of tricks and approaches to get you motivated will help.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Be your own dictator.</h2>\r\nAfter a year and a half of being on the <a href=\"https://www.ruled.me/guide-keto-diet/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Ketogenic diet</a>, I fell off the bandwagon this year when fall came around. The smell of spiced apple cider, the rich orange color of butternut squash soup, pumpkin scented candles and hot apple pie were just too much for me to turn down. After a month of eating all of my favorite fall foods, I knew I needed to get back to taking care of my body, but finding the motivation to get back on track was really tough. One night, I found myself reaching for the caramel apple slices, when my own voice in my head bellowed a loud and firm, \"NO.\" I stopped for a moment and stared at the creamy caramel like a puppy begging for table scraps, but the disciplinarian side of me held steadfast. There was no reasoning, no questioning, no second-guessing. In that moment, I had to tell myself <strong>no</strong>, and there was no way out of it.\r\n\r\nIn these moments, I conjure up images of my mother telling me no. I would always ask her, \"but why,\" and the answer was always the same: <em>because I said so</em>. Sometimes this is exactly the approach you need to take toward completing a particular goal. Can I just play my game for 5 more minutes? No. Can I just finish up this front-end animation that I\'m having fun with first? No. Can I just finish replying to this tweet before I finish my paper? <strong>No.</strong>\r\n\r\nThis approach is one of the most effective for me in the short-term, but it